</div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1580745755767_13307"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">With the diagrams out of the way, let’s get to work on the functional stuff.  First, let’s start with udev, which we’ll be using to map 3D printers’ USB connections to static names.  This will prevent the printers from showing up as different /dev/tty* names on reboot, which can mix up printer mappings to the different Octoprint instances.</p><h2 style="white-space:pre-wrap;">udev Config</h2><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">For udev, I am using the steps for USB mapping from <a href="http://www.prusamk2.com/using-multiple-3d-printers-single-raspberry-pi-octoprint/">this article</a>.  Unfortunately their article seems to have javascript preventing copy/paste, so I’ll be including commands here.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Run the following command to look for all the printers connected to your Pi.  Only have one printer at a time plugged in, and you’ll need to run through these steps for each printer.  If you have more than one 3D printer plugged into the Pi, you’ll have a hard time telling which one is which.  This command simply lists all the USB devices, so no root is needed:</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">udevadm info -q all -n /dev/ttyACM0 --attribute-walk</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">You’re going to want to look for several attributes to make sure you are assigning a port to a unique printer.  Model number and description are not enough, so look for unique attributes. For my example, I am looking for:  </p><p style="margin-left:40px;white-space:pre-wrap;" class="">=="2c99" </p><p style="margin-left:40px;white-space:pre-wrap;" class="">=="Original Prusa i3 MK3" </p><p style="margin-left:40px;white-space:pre-wrap;" class="">=="CZPX4433X004XK112233"  </p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Once you have the attributes, use the following command to create a new file:  sudo nano /etc/udev/rules.d/99-usb.rules  Filled out, here’s one line for a single printer, which maps that printer to /dev/printer3 no matter what port it’s plugged into and it keeps it between reboots.  <strong><em>Keep in mind my site wraps the following text around to two lines- it should be only one line per entry in the config file.</em></strong></p></div></div><div class="sqs-block markdown-block sqs-block-markdown" data-block-type="44" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1580745742739_35836"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p><code>SUBSYSTEM=="tty", ATTRS=="Original Prusa i3 MK3",ATTRS=="CZPX4433X004XK112233", SYMLINK+="printer3"</code></p>
</div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1580745742739_35900"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Repeat that process for each printer, having only one printer plugged in at a time.  The file 99-usb.rules just needs a single line for each device.<br>Go ahead and reboot here- you should be able to see each printer in /dev/ after reboot if they’re all connected.  If something’s not right, fix this first, it will make the rest of the setup easier later.</p><h2 style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Octoprint Config</h2><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Install and config of Octoprint is pretty simple, but I did some weird stuff here.  I had other configurations of Octoprint on different Raspberry Pi’s and copied the config folders over- you may need to fuss with this a little.  I will cover one instance here and show how I point to different configs, but I am using 3 different config directories that use a common Octoprint install.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">I’ve pulled the install steps from the Octoprint site here, but here’s the basic steps:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_26279"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">sudo apt install python-pip python-dev python-setuptools python-virtualenv git libyaml-dev build-essential
mkdir OctoPrint &amp;&amp; cd OctoPrint 
virtualenv venv
source venv/bin/activate
pip install pip --upgrade  
pip install octoprint  
exit  
sudo usermod -a -G tty pi  
sudo usermod -a -G dialout pi</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_26345"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">All of this is pretty standard stuff if you’re used to building Octoprint on a Raspberry Pi from scratch, but I’m including some of the breadcrumbs here so it’s not a complete mystery on how I did it.  If you’re new to Raspberry Pi and Octoprint, I’d suggest taking a detour now and get just one instance up and running.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Still with me?  Great- the next part for multiple instances really just means multiple Octoprint config directories- we will only have one copy of the actual Octoprint software.  You can copy your /home/pi/Octoprint folder to multiple copies, but I won’t be- I want all of my instances using the same code. For the purposes of this article my separate configs were copied from other systems into the folders /home/pi/.octoprint1, octoprint2, and octoprint4.</p><h3 style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Octoprint Services</h3><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">With your config folders setup, we need to run each Octoprint instance as a service.  While there’s documentation on the Octoprint services for older Pis, the Raspbian images have moved over to systemd and we need to write our own.  My versions are much simpler, and in my opinion easier to maintain.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">You can recreate these steps for each instance.  I’m using simple names and folders like octoprint1, octoprint2, etc. so it’s pretty easy to see what to change.  First, create a file with the following command:</p><pre><code>sudo nano /etc/systemd/system/octoprint1.service</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Here’s what should be in the file:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_21894"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">[Unit]
Description=OctoPrint1
After=network.target

[Service]
#ExecStart=/home/pi/OctoPrint/venv/bin/octoprint
User=pi
ExecStart=/home/pi/OctoPrint/venv/bin/octoprint serve --basedir /home/pi/.octoprint1/ --port=5001
Restart=always

[Install]
WantedBy=default.target</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_21968"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">This is pretty simple and simply starts the Octoprint program but has it listen on port 5001.  You need to change this port for each instance, and I have made instance #1 listen on 5001, #2 on 5002, etc.  Once that’s done, go ahead and enable the service with this command:</p><pre><code>sudo systemctl enable octoprint1.service</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Now you can rescan systemctl to look for new services with this command:</p><pre><code>sudo systemctl daemon-reload</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Now start the service octoprint1 (it gets its service name from the filename octoprint1.service):</p><pre><code>sudo service octoprint1 start</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">You should be able to go to your network address for your Pi and access port 5001 with an address like this: http://your-pi-address:5001</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Assuming you can access Octoprint on port 5001, go ahead and create new service files for each instance you want.  For this article there are three, but remember- you need the Octoprint config directory (/home/pi/.octoprint1, 2, 3) for each instance, and you need to change the port number and working directory in each service file.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Before proceeding, make sure you can get to each instance of Octoprint on ports 5001, 5002, and 5003.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">If you are OK with just using port numbers and no SSL, then you may wish to stop here.  The cool stuff is just getting started, and it’s how you can add better security to Octoprint.  Here we go, on to haproxy:</p><h3 style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Haproxy</h3><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Haproxy is designed to load balance multiple servers behind a single IP address.  While it’s outside the scope of this article, it allows you to remember one address (like a website) and the load balancer sends different requests and users on the backend to different servers.  As a user, you only see the “frontend” and the servers are in the “backend”.  A simple example is like a restaurant- you talk to the frontend staff like waitresses and waiters, while the cooks in the backend staff cook the food.  You get the food but you don’t see how it’s made.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Haproxy will have listeners on the frontend, and your Octoprint instances will be on the backend.  After this config is done you won’t be able to access Octoprint if haproxy isn’t running or has problems- in order to secure Octoprint we need to make sure everyone has to go through haproxy.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">First, install haproxy with:</p><pre><code>sudo apt install haproxy</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">The next step is to modify your Octoprint config files to make sure they listen only on your Pi’s internal network address.  We don’t want ports 5001, 5002, or 5003 on any other IPs.  We’re going to bind Octoprint to 127.0.0.1.  Let’s again modify just octoprint1, but you’ll need to repeat this step for each config.  We’re not changing port numbers in the config since we did that with the services file.  Run the following command to open octoprint1’s config file:</p><pre><code>nano /home/pi/.octoprint1/config.yaml</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">We’re going to do a few things while we’re here- first we’re going to disable access control- haproxy will be doing that.  Make sure the section for accessControl: looks like this:</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">accessControl:<br>  enabled: false</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">next find the ‘serial’ section and add the additionalPorts section to look like this, just make sure the indents match the config file.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">serial:                                                                                                                additionalPorts:                                                                                                     - /dev/printer1</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Just below it should be the server: section, add this indented option:</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">host: 127.0.0.1</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Go ahead and save and exit.  We just did three things- we disabled the access control in Octoprint since we’ll have haproxy doing authentication, we added the mapping for /dev/printer1 from our serial port stuff at the top of the article, and we bound Octoprint to 127.0.0.1.  If you are troubleshooting haproxy you can always come back and remote the host: 127.0.0.1 entry and Octoprint will listen on all IP addresses.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Go ahead and make this change now to all your other Octoprint instances.  Restart each Octoprint instance with the following commands:</p><pre><code>sudo service octoprint1 restart</code></pre><pre><code>sudo service octoprint2 restart</code></pre><pre><code>sudo service octoprint3 restart</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Congratulations, now you have three backend services for Octoprint!  Now we need to get to them.  In order to bind SSL certificates to each server, we need an IP address for each server.  We’re going to add those by switching the Pi over to a static IP address.  Make sure you pick IPs that are easy to remember, match your network, and are outside your router’s DHCP range.  For this project, they are .20 for the Pi, .21, .22, and .23 for the Octoprint servers.  In order to do this we’re going to modify the /etc/network/interfaces file.  If you’re logged in via SSH, be careful, you may lose access on reboot.  Again, I am using a wired connection (and even powering the Pi of a PoE adapter, but more on that later).</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Go ahead and run</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">sudo nano /etc/network/interfaces</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">And modify your file to look like this- note that only eth0 gets a gateway, eth0:1 and so on piggyback on that same connection.</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_65599"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code"># interfaces(5) file used by ifup(8) and ifdown(8)

# Please note that this file is written to be used with dhcpcd
# For static IP, consult /etc/dhcpcd.conf and 'man dhcpcd.conf'

# Include files from /etc/network/interfaces.d:
source-directory /etc/network/interfaces.d

auto eth0
allow-hotplug eth0
iface eth0 inet static
address 172.16.242.20
netmask 255.255.255.0
gateway 172.16.0.1

auto eth0:1
allow-hotplug eth0:1
iface eth0:1 inet static
address 172.16.0.21
netmask 255.255.255.0

auto eth0:2
allow-hotplug eth0:2
iface eth0:2 inet static
address 172.16.0.22
netmask 255.255.255.0

auto eth0:3
allow-hotplug eth0:3
iface eth0:3 inet static
address 172.16.0.23
netmask 255.255.255.0</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_65666"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Save the file and reboot your Pi- remember under this example that your Pi is now accessible from 172.16.0.20.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Next we’re going to add the haproxy configuration- so log back into your Pi and run the following command:</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">sudo nano /etc/haproxy/haproxy.cfg</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Go ahead and delete everything that’s in the config already, and replace it with this. This first section is likely very similar to the previous version, but you can see I’ve added a comment and a connection limit towards the end:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_70726"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">global
        log /dev/log    local0
        log /dev/log    local1 notice
        chroot /var/lib/haproxy
        stats socket /run/haproxy/admin.sock mode 660 level admin expose-fd listeners
        stats timeout 30s
        user haproxy
        group haproxy
        daemon

        # Default SSL material locations
        ca-base /etc/ssl/certs
        crt-base /etc/ssl/private

        # Default ciphers to use on SSL-enabled listening sockets.
        # For more information, see ciphers(1SSL). This list is from:
        #  https://hynek.me/articles/hardening-your-web-servers-ssl-ciphers/
        # An alternative list with additional directives can be obtained from
        #  https://mozilla.github.io/server-side-tls/ssl-config-generator/?server=haproxy
        ssl-default-bind-ciphers ECDH+AESGCM:DH+AESGCM:ECDH+AES256:DH+AES256:ECDH+AES128:DH+AES:RSA+AESGCM:RSA+AES:!$        ssl-default-bind-options no-sslv3
        tune.ssl.default-dh-param 2048
        #added 1-28-2020
        maxconn 2000</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_73380"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Now add the defaults section below where you added global:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_80234"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">defaults
        log     global
        mode    http
        option  httplog
        option  dontlognull
        timeout connect 5000
        timeout client  50000
        timeout server  50000
        errorfile 400 /etc/haproxy/errors/400.http
        errorfile 403 /etc/haproxy/errors/403.http
        errorfile 408 /etc/haproxy/errors/408.http
        errorfile 500 /etc/haproxy/errors/500.http
        errorfile 502 /etc/haproxy/errors/502.http
        errorfile 503 /etc/haproxy/errors/503.http
        errorfile 504 /etc/haproxy/errors/504.http

        #added 1-28-2020
        maxconn 2000
        retries 3
        option redispatch
        option http-server-close
        option forwardfor
        timeout connect 5s
        timeout client 15min
        timeout server 15min</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_80300"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">With that out of the way we can add some of the fun stuff- these commands will bind to the frontend on port 80, but all they will do is redirect you to HTTPS on 443 so you don’t get an error if you accidentally use HTTP instead of HTTPS when addressing the server:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_81887"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">#binds to .21 on port 80 just to redirect to the https port/name
frontend unsecured1
        bind 172.16.0.21:80
        redirect location https://one.printers.back7.co

#binds to .22 on port 80 just to redirect to the https port/name
frontend unsecured2
        bind 172.16.0.22:80
        redirect location https://two.printers.back7.co

#binds to .23 on port 80 just to redirect to the https port/name
frontend unsecured3
        bind 172.16.0.23:80
        redirect location https://three.printers.back7.co</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_81953"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Now for the HTTPS frontend listeners:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_83550"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">frontend public1
        bind 172.16.0.21:443 ssl crt /etc/ssl/certs/printers.doscher.com.pem
        default_backend octoprint1
        
frontend public2
    bind 172.16.0.22:443 ssl crt /etc/ssl/certs/servers.pem
        default_backend octoprint2
        
frontend public3
    bind 172.16.0.23:443 ssl crt /etc/ssl/certs/servers.pem
        default_backend octoprint3     </pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_83616"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Finally, our backend servers are added at the end of the config:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_110796"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">backend octoprint1
        reqrep ^([^\ :]*)\ /(.*)     \1\ /\2
        option forwardfor
        server octoprint1 127.0.0.1:5001

backend octoprint2
        reqrep ^([^\ :]*)\ /(.*)     \1\ /\2
        option forwardfor
        server octoprint1 127.0.0.1:5002

backend octoprint3
        reqrep ^([^\ :]*)\ /(.*)     \1\ /\2
        option forwardfor
        server octoprint1 127.0.0.1:5003</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_110863"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">All said and done, the config looks like this:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_112380"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">        ca-base /etc/ssl/certs
        crt-base /etc/ssl/private

        # Default ciphers to use on SSL-enabled listening sockets.
        # For more information, see ciphers(1SSL). This list is from:
        #  https://hynek.me/articles/hardening-your-web-servers-ssl-ciphers/
        # An alternative list with additional directives can be obtained from
        #  https://mozilla.github.io/server-side-tls/ssl-config-generator/?server=haproxy
        ssl-default-bind-ciphers ECDH+AESGCM:DH+AESGCM:ECDH+AES256:DH+AES256:ECDH+AES128:DH+AES:RSA+AESGCM:RSA+AES:!$        ssl-default-bind-options no-sslv3
        tune.ssl.default-dh-param 2048
        #added 1-28-2020
        maxconn 2000

defaults
        log     global
        mode    http
        option  httplog
        option  dontlognull
        timeout connect 5000
        timeout client  50000
        timeout server  50000
        errorfile 400 /etc/haproxy/errors/400.http
        errorfile 403 /etc/haproxy/errors/403.http
        errorfile 408 /etc/haproxy/errors/408.http
        errorfile 500 /etc/haproxy/errors/500.http
        errorfile 502 /etc/haproxy/errors/502.http
        errorfile 503 /etc/haproxy/errors/503.http
        errorfile 504 /etc/haproxy/errors/504.http

        #added 1-28-2020
        maxconn 2000
        retries 3
        option redispatch
        option http-server-close
        option forwardfor
        timeout connect 5s
        timeout client 15min
        timeout server 15min

#binds to .21 on port 80 just to redirect to the https port/name
frontend unsecured1
        bind 172.16.0.21:80
        redirect location https://one.printers.back7.co

#binds to .22 on port 80 just to redirect to the https port/name
frontend unsecured2
        bind 172.16.0.22:80
        redirect location https://two.printers.back7.co

#binds to .23 on port 80 just to redirect to the https port/name
frontend unsecured3
        bind 172.16.0.23:80
        redirect location https://three.printers.back7.co

frontend public1
        bind 172.16.0.21:443 ssl crt /etc/ssl/certs/printers.doscher.com.pem
        default_backend octoprint1

frontend public2
    bind 172.16.0.22:443 ssl crt /etc/ssl/certs/servers.pem
        default_backend octoprint2

frontend public3
    bind 172.16.0.23:443 ssl crt /etc/ssl/certs/servers.pem
        default_backend octoprint3 

backend octoprint1
        reqrep ^([^\ :]*)\ /(.*)     \1\ /\2
        option forwardfor
        server octoprint1 127.0.0.1:5001

backend octoprint2
        reqrep ^([^\ :]*)\ /(.*)     \1\ /\2
        option forwardfor
        server octoprint1 127.0.0.1:5002

backend octoprint3
        reqrep ^([^\ :]*)\ /(.*)     \1\ /\2
        option forwardfor
        server octoprint1 127.0.0.1:5003    </pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_112446"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">You may have noticed that the authentication components are missing- we’ll come back and add those in a bit.  If you want to authenticate to each Octoprint instance individually instead of using haproxy, modify your Octoprint configs and use this config as-is.</p><h3 style="white-space:pre-wrap;">TLS Certificates</h3><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">We also need to add our certificates- SSL/TLS certificates and cryptography are a complex subject and largely outside the scope of this article, so I’ll keep things simple.  One thing to be aware of- while we’ll use self-signed certificates and talk about how to trust them, we need to be careful about how we open ourselves up to attacks if an attacker misuses them.  I’ll first share the steps for using a commercial certificate provider- it’s more secure and works on more devices, but costs money.  I’ll also share how to use self-signed certs and trust them, which is free but a bit more risky.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><em>Commercial Certificates:</em></p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Commercial here simply means you’re using a CA (Certificate Authority) run as a business where you can buy certs.  Depending on the use, some are as cheap as $7.50US/year, but can run into the hundreds of dollars.  Cheap certs usually don’t support Subject Alternative Names, which essentially allows a single cert to work for multiple addresses (like we will use).  The request process is the same below, but beware- cheaper SSL companies will simply ignore the SAN values.  Here’s a single command to generate the files for a commercial cert:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_133248"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">openssl req -new -sha256 -nodes -out \one.printers.back7.co.csr -newkey rsa:2048 -keyout \one.printers.back7.co.key -config &lt;(
cat &lt;&lt;-EOF
[req]
default_bits = 2048
prompt = no
default_md = sha256
req_extensions = req_ext
distinguished_name = dn

[ dn ]
C=US
ST=California
L=Los Angeles
O=back7.co
OU=Research &amp; Development
emailAddress=bitbucket@back7.co
CN = one.printers.back7.co

[ req_ext ]
subjectAltName = @alt_names

[ alt_names ]
DNS.1 = one.printers.back7.co
DNS.2 = two.printers.back7.co
DNS.3 = three.printers.back7.co
DNS.4 = four.printers.back7.co
EOF
)</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_136877"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">The line:</p><pre><code>CN = one.printers.back7.co</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Is the line the cheap SSL certs will bind to, and ignore the alternate names.  The command run on the Pi (or any computer with openssl) will generate two files, the CSR (certificate request file) and the private key (ends in .key).  Both are text files you can simply cat or open with nano.  Your commercial CA will want the CSR to process- when they issue you a cert it will be a file/text that you can save as “one.printers.back7.co.crt” using my example here.  Once you have it downloaded, you can save it to the same folder as your .csr and .key files.  Once all three files are there, run this command to join the .crt and .key files into a .pem file for haproxy:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_145642"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">cat one.printers.back7.co.crt one.printers.back7.co.key &gt; one.printers.back7.co.pem</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_145708"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">The .pem file is needed for haproxy, but you need to treat all three files carefully.  The .csr is probably OK since it needs to be signed by the CA, but the .key is your private key and the .pem contains that key too.  Copy the .pem file into /etc/ssl/certs/ as the file servers.pem, which is referenced in the haproxy config.<br><br><em>Self-Signed Certificates:</em></p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">If you’re running a smaller lab or simply feel comfortable using self-signed certs, I have the steps below to help- but beware- while the certificates are technically the same kind, the difference is trust- and by managing some aspects of trust you’re taking on a much greater level of responsibility.  Simply put, your browser trusts the commercial certificate providers, so when they sign a cert and issue it to you, your devices trust it.  Self-signing means we’ll be signing the certs with our own CA, so if someone gets ahold of those CA certs and you trust them, you’re vulnerable.  You can also use the certs and not trust them, but you won’t easily know if they’ve been attacked or changed since your browser will always issue a warning.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">With those words of caution out of the way, here are the steps- still issue the csr but with a few different steps, and this time we’ll make our own root CA to sign them:</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Generate the root CA key:</p><pre><code>openssl genrsa -des3 -out rootCA.key 2048</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Generate the root CA pem:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code sqs-col-11 span-11 float float-left" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_161601"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">openssl req -x509 -new -nodes -key rootCA.key -sha256 -days 3650  -out rootCA.pem</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174777410_47172"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Generate the key file:</p><pre><code>openssl genrsa -out servers.key 2048</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Create a new CSR:</p><pre><code>openssl req -new -key servers.key -out servers.csr</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Create the options.ext file with the following contents:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_149130"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">authorityKeyIdentifier=keyid,issuer
basicConstraints=CA:FALSE
keyUsage = digitalSignature, nonRepudiation, keyEncipherment, dataEncipherment
subjectAltName = @alt_names

[alt_names]
DNS.1 = one.printers.back7.co
DNS.2 = two.printers.back7.co
DNS.3 = three.printers.back7.co</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_152087"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Issue the cert using our local root CA:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_160136"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">openssl x509 -req -in servers.csr -CA rootCA.pem -CAkey rootCA.key -CAcreateserial -out servers.crt -days 3650 -sha256 -extfile options.ext</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174785502_160202"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">From here you should have your server.crt and server.key, combine them to make the servers.pem:</p><pre><code>cat server.crt server.key &gt; server.pem</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Save that server.pem file in /etc/ssl/certs/, but use sudo to do it- standard users can’t write to that folder.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Go ahead and restart haproxy with</p><pre><code>sudo service haproxy restart</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">If it fails, run this command to see the error:</p><pre><code>sudo haproxy -f /etc/haproxy/haproxy.cfg</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Go back through and check- but if there are errors in the article here please comment below or send me a note.  Due to the complexity of the config I may not be able to support everyone’s variations.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Now you should have TLS/SSL/HTTPS setup and listening on all three IPs.  For the certs to match, you need to trust them (more on this in a bit) and you need to make sure you access them by the names in the cert.  So 172.16.0.21 should be addressable by one.printers.back7.co, etc.  That means if you go to https://one.printers.back7.co it should resolve to that IP.  You’ll need to create DNS or hosts entries for each printer.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">As for trust- this is a lengthy topic and I’m focused on the essentials here- so the rootCA.pem can be imported into your Windows, Mac, or Linux certificate stores under “Trusted Certification Authorities” under Windows, for example- and it will allow your browser to trust the certs.  Firefox requires another step: under about:config, search for “security.enterprise_roots.enabled” and change it to true.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Here’s the disclaimer- trusting your rootCA created in the steps above means that your system trusts any certificate signed by those files.  If you get your Raspberry Pi hacked, they can be used to generate SSL certificates your browser trusts.  This is where personal responsibility comes in- if you don’t manage those files properly or responsibly, you open the door to all kinds of nasty attacks.  If you’re uncomfortable with this, remove the root CA and simply use the commercial steps.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">Haproxy Authentication</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">For the last section, we’re going to add basic authentication to the HTTP listeners in haproxy.  Generate passwords via the command line with this command:</p><pre><code>mkpasswd --method=sha-512</code></pre><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">After that, crack open your /etc/haproxy/haproxy.cfg file and add this section just after the global section:</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581187361418_18869"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">userlist basic-auth-list
       group is-regular-user users jay
       group is-admin users admin

       user admin password $somereallylongstring
       user jay password $someotherreallylongstring1</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581187361418_22242"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">You can see the $somereallylongstring sample here, that’s where the password hashes you just generated will go.  For each frontend in haproxy, add these lines, changing the hostname and the backend name accordingly.  These add an access control list to the frontend, and then redirect if authenticated.  Don’t add these to the standard HTTP/port 80 listeners, we don’t want to send our passwords over the clear.  Change the whole frontend section for each listener public1, 2, and 3 to look like this, but with IPs and server names changed.  This will enforce the access list on each frontend you define.  Note- this looks a bit different that the first haproxy example.</p></div></div><div class="sqs-block code-block sqs-block-code" data-block-type="23" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581187361418_33430"><div class="sqs-block-content"><pre class="source-code">frontend public1
        bind 172.16.0.21:443 ssl crt /etc/ssl/certs/servers.pem
        acl is-draw hdr_dom(host) -i one.printers.back7.co
        acl authorized http_auth(basic-auth-list)
        use_backend octoprint1 if is-draw</pre></div></div><div class="sqs-block html-block sqs-block-html" data-block-type="2" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581187361418_33496"><div class="sqs-block-content"><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;">You can optionally add authentication on the backend as well, but considering we are running haproxy locally on the same host as Octoprint, it is unnecessary.  If you run haproxy on a separate host, you need to take a more complicated approach.</p><p class="" style="white-space:pre-wrap;"><br></p></div></div><div class="sqs-block image-block sqs-block-image" data-block-type="5" id="block-yui_3_17_2_1_1581174777410_133176"><div class="sqs-block-content">















  

    
  
